explanation: This solution uses a priority queue to efficiently merge k sorted linked lists. It first initializes a dummy node and a priority queue. Then, it pushes the head of each list into the priority queue. The priority queue ensures that the node with the smallest value is always at the top. The solution then iteratively pops the smallest node from the priority queue, adds it to the result list, and pushes the next node from the same list into the priority queue. This approach ensures that the resulting list is sorted and has a time complexity of O(N log k), where N is the total number of nodes and k is the number of lists.

